   {:e #blake3 "c7d31d321d4a59132bbbfc4cb6e96c10f5a7e041edc558a0f2cc639a729b4440" :a :db/ident :v :harvest/session-braid-user-1774043763 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "c7d31d321d4a59132bbbfc4cb6e96c10f5a7e041edc558a0f2cc639a729b4440" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-125249858a55b7c2; Session entity: :recon/trace-267e923557655245; Session entity: :recon/trace-22574a0ad5abd5fa; OUTPUT-AS-OBSERVATION — IMPLEMENTATION DESIGN: Three changes to the command pipeline. (1) In each knowledge-producing command's run function (task close, task create, transact, spec create), after building the result datoms but BEFORE writing the transaction, append auto-observation datoms to the SAME Vec<Datom>. The observation entity gets: :db/ident ':auto-obs/{command}-{tx_wall_time}', :exploration/body (the close reason or rationale string), :exploration/confidence (command-type inferred), :exploration/category ':exploration.cat/auto-command', :exploration/source (command name), :exploration/content-hash (BLAKE3 of body). (2) parse_spec_refs on the body text to extract INV-*/ADR-*/NEG-* references. For each resolved ref, add :exploration/related-spec Ref datom linking the auto-obs to the spec entity. This creates the graph edges that power spec_graph_neighbors and compile_demonstrations. (3) The auto-obs datoms are in the SAME transaction as the command's primary datoms — atomic, no extra IO, no cache invalidation. The per-command changes are ~5 lines each: extract body text (reason/rationale), call a shared auto_obs_datoms(body, command_name, tx) helper, append to datoms vec. CONSIDERATION: braid observe already creates explicit observations — auto-obs must NOT duplicate these. When the command IS observe, skip auto-obs (the explicit observation IS the output). Also skip for read-only commands (status, query, seed) since they don't produce write transactions.; OUTPUT-AS-OBSERVATION — P(t) PROGRESS METRIC: Alongside the output-as-observation change, add P(t) = closed/(closed+open) as a progress metric in braid status. Currently F(S)=0.67 doesn't move despite 44 tasks closed. P(t) = 434/788 = 0.55 — this reflects actual progress. Both metrics serve different purposes: F(S) = formal verification quality, P(t) = implementation velocity. Display both in status: 'coherence: F(S)=0.67 P(t)=0.55'. P(t) is trivially computable from task_counts() which already exists. ALSO: harvest urgency should weight by knowledge production rate: novel entities (new :db/ident) count 10x, routine updates (task close, status change) count 1x. This prevents alert fatigue during batch operations. TRACES TO: INV-BILATERAL-001, INV-GUIDANCE-021, INV-HARVEST-005.; OUTPUT-AS-OBSERVATION — THE CORE INSIGHT: Every braid command that modifies the store already produces structured JSON output containing spec refs, entity IDs, and domain vocabulary. The output IS the observation. Not a summary derived from output — the output itself, written as an :auto-obs/* datom in the SAME transaction. This eliminates braid observe ceremony for 80% of knowledge capture. The remaining 20% (pure insights, design decisions, questions not triggered by a command) still uses explicit braid observe. The store comonad principle from Session 028: every store interaction IS an observation. We said it — now we make it literal. IMPLEMENTATION: In each command's run function, after building the CommandOutput JSON, if the JSON contains parseable spec refs (via parse_spec_refs on the stringified JSON), append an :auto-obs/* entity to the same transaction with: body = close_reason or rationale, spec_refs = parsed refs, confidence = inferred from command type (close=0.9, create=0.8, transact=0.7, observe=explicit), source = command name. Zero new commands. Zero ceremony. Zero performance cost (datoms already being written). TRACES TO: INV-STORE-014, INV-HARVEST-009, INV-GUIDANCE-014, ADR-GUIDANCE-002.; OUTPUT-AS-OBSERVATION — VERIFICATION PLAN: Three layers. (1) Unit test: auto_obs_datoms('implemented X for INV-STORE-001', 'task_close', tx) produces datoms with correct :exploration/body, :exploration/confidence=0.9, :exploration/category=auto-command, and :exploration/related-spec Ref to INV-STORE-001 entity. (2) Integration test: call task::close() on a task with spec refs in title. Verify the resulting transaction contains BOTH :task/status=closed AND :auto-obs/* entity with linked spec refs. Count datoms: should be close_datoms + auto_obs_datoms in one tx. (3) E2E test: braid task close t-xxx --reason 'test reason' → braid query --attribute :exploration/category → verify ':exploration.cat/auto-command' datom exists with correct body. Also: braid observe 'explicit obs' → verify NO duplicate auto-obs created (explicit observe skips auto-obs). Also: braid status (read command) → verify NO auto-obs created.; Session entity: :recon/trace-fe4dc1053256f076; DOG-FOODING FRICTION POINTS — the 5 things that slow me down most:\n\n1. F(S) IS INERT. It has been 0.67 the entire session despite closing 44 tasks, adding 68 tests, creating 4 EPICs, and implementing 3 major subsystems (TSV, spec_graph_neighbors, compile-to-prompt). The metric does not reflect the work. Root cause: the V (validation) component requires formal FBW witnesses, not just tests existing. And the C (coverage) component checks spec-impl link density, which doesn't change much when I'm implementing kernel functions (they don't have :impl/implements links by default). F(S) measures FORMAL VERIFICATION STATUS, not IMPLEMENTATION PROGRESS. These are different things and the system conflates them. PROPOSED FIX: add a separate progress metric P(t) = closed_tasks / total_tasks that responds to actual work, alongside F(S) for formal verification.\n\n2. HARVEST URGENCY ALERT FATIGUE. The NEG-HARVEST-001 warning fires after ~10 transactions. During active coding, I hit 10 tx in 3-4 minutes. The warning becomes noise I reflexively ignore. The urgency formula treats all tx equally, but a batch of task closes (10 tx in 30 seconds) is NOT the same as 10 knowledge-producing observations over an hour. PROPOSED FIX: weight urgency by knowledge production rate, not raw tx count. Task closes and status checks should barely register; novel observations should register heavily.\n\n3. THE TASK TITLE PROBLEM IS ONLY HALF SOLVED. short_title strips BACKGROUND sections from list display, but the FULL title is still stored as one massive string in :task/title. This bloats the store, slows queries, and makes the JSON output huge. Task-as-ACP (structured task entities with :task/background, :task/acceptance, :task/approach as separate attributes) is the real fix but isn't implemented. Every task I created this session crammed 500+ chars into the title field.\n\n4. PARALLEL AGENT FILE CONFLICTS. I launched 3 agents in parallel (TSV-TEST, CTP-1, AR-2) on disjoint file sets, but the AR-4 agent later modified MethodologyGaps in guidance.rs which broke my CTP-2 changes in seed.rs. The dependency was STRUCTURAL (shared type), not FILE-based. Braid's topology system tracks file-level coupling but not type-level coupling. When Agent A adds a field to a struct that Agent B uses, the conflict is invisible until cargo check fails.\n\n5. CEREMONY COST OF BRAID OBSERVE. Each braid observe call costs ~3 seconds (store load + reconciliation scan + datom write). Over 44 tasks, I ran observe ~15 times = 45 seconds of pure ceremony. This doesn't include the TOKEN cost of formulating the observation text. The Zero-Cost Methodology (auto-observation from command outputs) would eliminate this, but it's not implemented. The irony: the observe command is the MOST important for knowledge capture, but its ceremony cost makes agents skip it.; Session entity: :recon/trace-f457c35cf3cb081a; Session entity: :recon/trace-2a4c915ea31563c8; Session entity: :recon/trace-10829a6126d0ad19; Session entity: :recon/trace-d59b6ad6d06a527a; Session entity: :recon/trace-46f79cb7072e74a3; FIRST-PRINCIPLES PLAN REVISION — The dog-fooding feedback reveals that our plan optimizes for the WRONG metric. We have been optimizing for F(S) (formal verification status) and task count. But the feedback says: (1) F(S) is inert — doesn't respond to work. (2) Task titles are bloated — the observe→task pipeline produces verbose artifacts. (3) Ceremony cost is high — braid observe takes 3s per call. (4) Alert fatigue — harvest urgency fires too often. All four friction points share ONE root cause: the system optimizes for COMPLETENESS OF RECORDS rather than VELOCITY OF INSIGHT. Every feature we've built makes the store more complete (more datoms, more spec refs, more traces). But the agent's primary need is not completeness — it's ACTIVATION. The agent needs to be in the right cognitive state to produce correct output. The compile-to-prompt work (CTP-1..5) addresses this for seeds. But the same principle applies to EVERY touchpoint: status should activate, not just report. Observe should activate, not just record. The plan should be revised to make ACTIVATION QUALITY the primary metric, with completeness as a secondary effect.; Session entity: :recon/trace-6c236bc3e618eac5; Session entity: :recon/trace-e2caa89bc96d816c; Session entity: :recon/trace-1cd307f1d6c16dae; DOG-FOODING OVERALL ASSESSMENT — Braid is at an inflection point.\n\nTHE SYSTEM WORKS. The harvest/seed cycle, R(t) routing, TSV output, spec_graph_neighbors, ACP projections, short_title — these are not aspirational features. They are LIVE, TESTED, and MAKING MY WORK MEASURABLY BETTER. I can feel the difference between working with braid (structured, traceable, recoverable) and working without it (ad-hoc, fragile, lossy).\n\nTHE SELF-BOOTSTRAP IS REAL. Session 029 used braid to build braid: spec_graph_neighbors was crystallized as a braid observation, tasked as a braid task, implemented, tested, and immediately used by the next braid observe call. The system is eating its own cooking and the food is getting better with every iteration.\n\nTHE COMPOUNDING IS VISIBLE. 434 closed tasks = 434 demonstrations for compile_demonstrations. 28,559 datoms = 28,559 facts for seed context assembly. 93% spec coverage = 93% structural connectivity for spec_graph_neighbors. Each session makes the next session better because the store grows monotonically.\n\nTHE GAP IS BETWEEN FORMAL AND PRACTICAL. F(S) says 0.67 but my practical experience says the system is at ~85% of Stage 1 completeness. The formal metric lags the practical reality because formal verification (FBW witnesses) is harder to produce than working code. This is the right tension — formal metrics SHOULD lag practical progress because they require higher evidence standards. But the lag shouldn't be SO large that the metric feels disconnected.\n\nTHE SINGLE BIGGEST IMPROVEMENT WOULD BE: Auto-observation. Making every knowledge-producing command automatically capture an observation datom as a side-effect. This would eliminate the ceremony cost of braid observe, increase the observation corpus (which feeds compile_demonstrations and spec_graph_neighbors), and close the 'Implemented But Not Wired' gap for knowledge capture. The Zero-Cost Methodology EPIC exists but is not implemented. It should be the #1 priority for Session 030.\nSession entity: :task/t-a62c2bb0; Session entity: :task/t-86c7d255; Session entity: :task/t-b082eb37; Session entity: :task/t-4582c61a; Session entity: :task/t-7d5553c2" :op :assert}
